# 🎤 NEXUS — HackIllinois 2026 Pitch Script

> **Total time:** ~5 minutes
> **Format:** Every word below is written out. Read these lines exactly or adapt them to your natural speaking style.
> **Speaker tags:** Assign SPEAKER 1 (the storyteller) and SPEAKER 2 (the technical voice). If you're solo, just flow through it.

---

## PART 1 — The Hook *(30 seconds)*

**SPEAKER 1:**

"In March 2023, Silicon Valley Bank collapsed in forty-eight hours. Billions of dollars in quantitative trading models kept running as if nothing had changed. Those models read price charts, volatility curves, and historical correlations — but none of them could read a headline.

Every major financial crisis — 2008, COVID, Russia-Ukraine — exposed the exact same blind spot. Quantitative models are excellent at reading markets, but they cannot read the world.

Today, there is no tool that answers a deceptively simple question: how much should I trust my models right now?

We built that tool. It is called NEXUS."

---

## PART 2 — What NEXUS Does *(45 seconds)*

**SPEAKER 1:**

"NEXUS is a real-time Model Risk Engine. It continuously scrapes live global news from over ninety sources — Reuters, BBC, the Financial Times, the New York Times, Al Jazeera, Bloomberg — and uses AI to measure how much those real-world events are undermining the assumptions that statistical trading models depend on.

Think of it like a weather system for financial models. Pilots check turbulence reports before trusting autopilot. Sailors check the forecast before trusting their charts. NEXUS lets traders and risk managers check real-world narrative pressure before trusting their quantitative strategies.

But here is the key difference between NEXUS and a news feed — NEXUS does not just show you headlines. It quantifies them. It gives you a single number — the Model Risk Index — that tells you whether markets are behaving statistically normally, or whether something in the real world is breaking the patterns your models rely on."

---

## PART 3 — How We Use Modal and AI *(90 seconds)*

> [!IMPORTANT]
> This is the section judges care about most. Nail this.

**SPEAKER 2:**

"Let me walk you through the AI pipeline — because this is where the real engineering lives.

NEXUS runs a four-stage pipeline, and **Modal is at the center of two of those stages**.

**Stage one is scraping.** Every two minutes, our backend scrapes over ninety live RSS feeds and the NewsAPI. These are real headlines happening right now — not sample data, not mock data. Real news from real sources.

**Stage two is AI embedding — and this is where Modal comes in.** Every incoming headline and story body gets sent to our **Modal-deployed Embedder**. This is an `all-MiniLM-L6-v2` sentence transformer model running on an **NVIDIA T4 GPU** in the cloud, hosted entirely on Modal. It converts each story into a three-hundred-eighty-four dimensional semantic vector — a mathematical fingerprint of what that story *means*.

We did not just make simple API calls to Modal. We built a **custom batching system** on top of it. Our embedder service uses a thread-safe queue that coalesces individual embedding calls into batches of up to thirty-two texts, then sends them to Modal in a single GPU round-trip. This means if thirty-two stories arrive at the same time, they all share one network call instead of thirty-two. That is a ninety-seven percent reduction in Modal overhead.

**Stage three is also powered by Modal.** When NEXUS discovers a story that does not fit any existing narrative — meaning it is semantically distant from everything we have seen before — it needs to create a brand new narrative direction and give it a name. For that, we deploy a second Modal class: the **Labeler**, which runs **Qwen 2.5, a half-billion-parameter instruction-tuned language model**. We wrote a custom few-shot prompt that tells it: you are a financial risk analyst, produce a concise three-to-five word label for this headline, include specific entity names, be specific not generic. So instead of naming something 'Banking Crisis,' it names it 'SVB Bank Run Collapse.' Instead of 'Trade Policy,' it names it 'China Chip Export Ban.' Every single narrative name you see on the dashboard was generated by this model on Modal.

**Stage four is scoring.** For each narrative, we compute two signals. Surprise — how unexpected recent developments are. And Impact — how economically significant the narrative is. These combine into the overall Model Risk Index. The scoring uses a custom multi-signal heuristic — five independent signals including semantic distance, keyword severity, trend-break language, magnitude words, and entity importance — all blended with exponential moving averages. This gives us low-latency scoring with no additional API calls.

So to summarize our Modal usage: we deploy **two AI models** on Modal. The Embedder gives every piece of news a semantic meaning. The Labeler gives every new narrative a human-readable name. Together, they are the intelligence layer that turns raw news into structured, quantitative risk."

