## 🧠 Judge Questions — Written-Out Answers

### "How exactly do you use Modal?"

"We deploy two Modal classes. The first is our Embedder — it runs the all-MiniLM-L6-v2 sentence transformer on an NVIDIA T4 GPU. Every incoming news story gets sent to this model and comes back as a three-hundred-eighty-four dimensional vector. The second is our Labeler — it runs Qwen 2.5, a half-billion parameter instruction-tuned language model, on CPU. Whenever NEXUS discovers a brand-new narrative direction, the Labeler generates a concise, entity-specific three-to-five word name for it. Both classes are deployed with `modal deploy`, called remotely from our Python backend using [cls().method.remote()](file:///c:/Users/krish/OneDrive/Hackillinois%20frontend/backend/services/embedder.py#59-71), and auto-scale based on demand. We also built a custom batching layer on top of Modal — individual embedding calls get coalesced into batches of up to thirty-two before hitting the GPU, so we minimize network round-trips."

### "What AI or ML models do you use?"

"Three models in total. First, all-MiniLM-L6-v2, a sentence transformer that produces three-hundred-eighty-four dimensional semantic embeddings — deployed on a Modal T4 GPU. Second, Qwen 2.5-0.5B-Instruct, an instruction-tuned large language model that generates narrative labels — deployed on Modal CPU. Third, a custom multi-signal heuristic scorer that computes surprise and impact from five independent signals — semantic distance from the narrative centroid, high-impact keyword detection, surprise-language detection, magnitude-language detection, and a direction base signal. This runs locally with zero latency and no API dependency."

### "Is this real data?"

"Yes. We scrape over ninety live RSS feeds — Reuters, BBC, Financial Times, New York Times, CNBC, Bloomberg, the Associated Press, Al Jazeera and more. We also pull from NewsAPI. Every narrative on this dashboard was discovered from news that was actually published today. Nothing is pre-loaded, nothing is mock data."

### "How is this different from just using ChatGPT?"

"ChatGPT is a chatbot — you ask it a question and get an answer. NEXUS is an always-on monitoring system. It runs continuously, maintains a persistent vector database of narrative state in ChromaDB, computes quantitative risk metrics in real time, and does automated surveillance of ninety-plus news sources every two minutes. You cannot get that from a chat interface."

### "What is the tech stack?"

"FastAPI and Uvicorn for the backend. ChromaDB as our semantic vector database with cosine similarity and HNSW indexing. Modal for cloud GPU and CPU inference — hosting our sentence transformer and our LLM. Python throughout the backend. The frontend is vanilla HTML, CSS, and JavaScript with Chart.js for time series charts and Three.js for the three-dimensional vector space visualization. Server-Sent Events for real-time push updates to the dashboard."

### "How does the risk score work?"

"Each narrative has two signals — surprise and impact — each computed as an exponential moving average with alpha of zero-point-three-five over the last fifty data points. The narrative's composite risk is the geometric mean of surprise times impact, blended sixty-five to thirty-five with the peak risk from the last ten events. The overall Model Risk Index is the event-count-weighted average across all active narratives."

### "What would you do with more time?"

"Three things. First, alert thresholds — automatic notifications to traders when model risk crosses critical levels. Second, backtesting — run historical news from March 2020 or March 2023 through the pipeline and show that NEXUS would have flagged the risk before markets moved. Third, direct API integration with trading platforms so model risk can be consumed as a live signal by quantitative strategies."

### "Why not just track VIX or volatility?"

"VIX tells you that markets are scared. NEXUS tells you *why* they should be. VIX is a market-derived metric — it only moves after markets move. NEXUS reads the news *before* it hits prices. More importantly, VIX is a single number with no decomposition. NEXUS gives you the specific narratives driving risk, the surprise and impact of each one, and their semantic relationships. It is an interpretable, narrative-level layer that VIX cannot provide."

